                            <span class="caption-truncated">The 677 Washington Blvd. site, which includes Stamford’s largest vacant office property, has been sold for $33 million.</span>
                                        </div>
                    </div>
                            
                    <div class="asset_photo" data-slide-id="2">
                        <div class="img-wrap">
                            <amp-img class="amp-img" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20200529061749im_/https://s.hdnux.com/photos/70/13/41/14727237/5/375x250.jpg" width="375" height="249" layout="fixed">
                            </amp-img>
                        </div>
                                                                                                                        <div>
                            <div class="mediasale"> <span class="icon"> </span> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20200529061749/http://stamfordadvocate.mycapture.com/mycapture/remoteimage.asp?backtext=Back%20to%20Stamford%20Advocate&amp;image=https://s.hdnux.com/photos/70/13/41/14727237/5/628x471.jpg&amp;pricingsheetid=2241">Buy this photo</a></div>
                            <span class="credit">
                                                Photo: Michael Cummo / Hearst Connecticut Media
                                            </span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="caption">
                                            <div class="slide-count">Image 2 of 3 </div>
                            <input type="checkbox" class="more-state-toggle" id="more-state-toggle-14727237"/>
                            <span class="caption-truncated">UBS’ local offices are located in the Royal Bank of Scotland-owned building, right, at 600 Washington Blvd., in downtown Stamford, Conn. In 2016, it moved out of the office complex, at left, at 677 Washington</span>
                                            <span class="caption-full-text">UBS’ local offices are located in the Royal Bank of Scotland-owned building, right, at 600 Washington Blvd., in downtown Stamford, Conn. In 2016, it moved out of the office complex, at left, at 677 Washington Blvd.</span>
                            <span class="truncated"></span>
                            <label for="more-state-toggle-14727237" class="more-trigger caption-btn"></label>
                                        </div>
                    </div>
                            
                    <div class="asset_photo" data-slide-id="3">
                        <div class="img-wrap">
                            <amp-img class="amp-img" src="https://web.archive.org/web/20200529061749im_/https://s.hdnux.com/photos/70/13/41/14727238/5/375x250.jpg" width="375" height="249" layout="fixed">
                            </amp-img>
                        </div>
                                                                                                                        <div>
                            <div class="mediasale"> <span class="icon"> </span> <a href="https://web.archive.org/web/20200529061749/http://stamfordadvocate.mycapture.com/mycapture/remoteimage.asp?backtext=Back%20to%20Stamford%20Advocate&amp;image=https://s.hdnux.com/photos/70/13/41/14727238/5/628x471.jpg&amp;pricingsheetid=2241">Buy this photo</a></div>
                            <span class="credit">
                                                Photo: Michael Cummo / Hearst Connecticut Media
                                            </span>
                        </div>
                        <div class="caption">
                                            <div class="slide-count">Image 3 of 3 </div>
                            <input type="checkbox" class="more-state-toggle" id="more-state-toggle-14727238"/>
                            <span class="caption-truncated">The building at 600 Washington Blvd., in downtown Stamford, Conn., houses the local offices of Royal Bank of Scotland and UBS.</span>
                                        </div>
                    </div>
                            </amp-base-carousel>
                                                                                                                                                                                        <meta content="text/html; charset=utf-8"><p>For the past few months, city officials had been working with UBS on the sale of 677 Washington&rsquo;s &ldquo;underlying property&rdquo; to the current building owners, said Thomas Madden, the city&rsquo;s economic development director.</p>
                                                                                                                                                    <meta content="text/html; charset=utf-8"><p>&ldquo;Having the entire property, land and buildings, under one ownership will help strengthen the positioning of the building in the market, as any prospective new tenants now only have to work with one owner, as opposed to two,&rdquo; Madden said. &ldquo;This change in ownership allows for modification of the building and entrances on the property. There is still additional square footage that can be built on the site, and we look forward to working with the owners on any future plans for the site.&rdquo;</p>
                                                                                                                                                    <meta content="text/html; charset=utf-8"><p>The city is working with several parties interested in leasing the building, according to Madden. He hopes to see a tenant move into the complex within the next year.</p>
                                                                                                                                                    <meta content="text/html; charset=utf-8"><p>&ldquo;We want to make sure that any company that comes into the building has the support of the Stamford business ecosystem that will allow for the long-term success of the company, but will also support the city and the Stamford downtown businesses,&rdquo; Madden said.</p>
                                                                                                                                                    <meta content="text/html; charset=utf-8"><p><strong>Turbulent history</strong></p>
                                                                                    <div class="amp-ad">
                <amp-ad height="250" width="300" type="doubleclick" data-slot="/36117602/hnp-stamfordadvocate.mobile/Business" json="{&quot;targeting&quot;:{&quot;page_type&quot;:&quot;article&quot;,&quot;position&quot;:&quot;STF&quot;,&quot;DIV_ID&quot;:&quot;S300&quot;,&quot;page_type2&quot;:&quot;Amp&quot;}}" rtc-config="{&quot;vendors&quot;:{&quot;aps&quot;:{&quot;PUB_ID&quot;:&quot;3070&quot;,&quot;PARAMS&quot;:{&quot;amp&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}},&quot;prebidappnexus&quot;: {&quot;PLACEMENT_ID&quot;: 18920456, &quot;ACCOUNT_ID&quot;: &quot;403ca951-6d92-4f2b-816a-0cf8a69217d8&quot;}},&quot;timeoutMillis&quot;: 750}">
                </amp-ad>
            </div>
                                                                                    <meta content="text/html; charset=utf-8"><p>AVG&rsquo;s $54 million outlay for 677 Washington&rsquo;s mortgage compared with an approximately $146 million balance, according to data from mortgage-tracking firm Trepp.</p>
                                                                                                                                                    <meta content="text/html; charset=utf-8"><p>The loan belonged to a pool of mortgages bundled in a commercial mortgage-backed security. The property&rsquo;s note, which originated in 2004 with a balance of about $230 million, fell into default when it failed to pay off by its maturity date in October 2016, according to Trepp.</p>
                                                                                                                                                    <meta content="text/html; charset=utf-8"><p>Reflecting the building&rsquo;s travails, 677 Washington&rsquo;s appraised value plunged at the beginning of this year to about $37 million.</p>
                                                                                                                                                    <meta content="text/html; charset=utf-8"><p>UBS was scheduled to make its last lease payment for 677 Washington in October 2016, but it has been obligated to maintain the building until the lease expires at the end of this year, according to Trepp.</p>
                                                                                                                                                    <meta content="text/html; charset=utf-8"><p>Approximately 900 UBS employees now work at 600 Washington Blvd., compared with a reported Stamford workforce of as many as 4,400 before the 2008 financial crisis. The company has sharply reduced its local contingent, as it has restructured in the wake of major losses in recent years.</p>
                                                                                                                                                    <meta content="text/html; charset=utf-8"><p>Most of the current employees work in operational positions, and none hold trading jobs, UBS officials have said in previous statements.</p>
                                                                                                                                                    <meta content="text/html; charset=utf-8"><p>RBS&rsquo; own struggles &mdash; it has laid off about 700 Stamford employees in the past three years &mdash; created the space for UBS&rsquo; move.</p>
                                                                                                                                                    <meta content="text/html; charset=utf-8"><p>The idleness of 677 Washington, which was built in 1996 and renovated in 2001, has spiked Stamford&rsquo;s citywide office vacancy rates, which now run at approximately 30 percent.</p>
                                                                                                                                                    <meta content="text/html; charset=utf-8"><p>Business leaders and city officials have proposed for the property a number of new uses, including apartments and a hotel. Some have suggested converting the former trading floor into a convention center.</p>
                                                                                                                                                    <meta content="text/html; charset=utf-8"><em>
<p>pschott@scni.com; 203-964-2236; Twitter: @paulschott</p>
</em>
                                                                                        
